<TITLE> Palestinian investor conference likely in May:PM </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 JERUSALEM, Feb 19 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The Palestinian government expects to hold a major investors conference in Bethlehem around mid-May, Prime Minster Salam Fayyad said on Tuesday. The conference, part of efforts to boost the economy as Palestinians take part in US-backed peace talks with Israel, was first announced in December by British Prime Minister Gordon Brown. At the time, Brown said Britain and the United States would host the event in March or April in the West Bank city. Fayyad, however, told a meeting of Jewish-American leaders in Jerusalem that his "best guess" was now that the conference would be held "immediately after" a World Economic Forum event organised for Sharm el-Sheikh in Egypt. The WEF has scheduled its Middle East event for May 18-20. US officials said the conference date would be set by the Palestinian Authority. The meeting at Bethlehem aims to follow on from a gathering of foreign governments and international institutions in Paris in December, when $7.7 billion in aid was pledged to the Palestinians over the next three years. Fayyad said holding the event for private investors in the West Bank was in itself a signal to the world that it was possible to do business in the Palestinian territori
